
DAX Aggregation Functions:

DAX Sum: 
              Adds all the numbers in a column.
Syntax:
              SUM(<column>)
Ex:  Find the total selling price of all products.
 SUM Total Price = SUM (Sales [Price])
	
DAX SumX: 
                Returns the sum of an expression evaluated for each row in a table.
Syntax:
               SUMX (<table, expression>)
Ex:    Find the total profit of all sales.
SumX=Totalprofit=SUMX(Sheet1,(Sheet1[Price]-          Sheet1[Cost])*Sheet1[Quantity])
DAX Max:
             Returns the largest numeric value in a column, or between two scalar expressions.
Syntax:
                MAX(<column>)
Ex: Find the maximum selling price.
       Max Price = MAX(Sales[Price])
                       
DAX MaxX:
          Evaluates an expression for each row of a table and return the largest numeric value.
Syntax:
               MAXX(<table, expression>)
EX: Find the maximum profit per product.
Max= max per product = MAXX(Sheet1,Sheet1[Price]-Sheet1[Cost])
DAX Min: 
      Returns the smallest numeric value in a column, or between two scalar expressions.
Syntax:
              MIN(<column>)
EX: Find Minimum sales price
Min Price = MIN(Sales[Price])


DAX MinX: 
             Returns the smallest numeric value that results from evaluating an expression for each row of a table.
Syntax:
            MINX(<table, expression>)
EX: Find the minimum profit per product.
       Min Profit = MINX(Sales, Sales[Price] - Sales[Cost])

DAX Average: 
               This function calculates the average of the values contained in the provided column as input. 
Syntax:
                   AVERAGE(<column>)
EX: Find the average selling price.
        Avg Price = AVERAGE(Sales[Price])

DAX AverageX:
                  Calculates the average (arithmetic mean) of a set of expressions evaluated over a table.
Syntax:
             AVERAGEX(<table>,<expression>)

EX: Find the average profit per product.
       Avg Profit = AVERAGEX(Sales, Sales[Price] - Sales[Cost])

DAX Product:
            Returns the product of the numbers in a column.
Syntax:
           PRODUCT(<column>)
EX: Find the product (multiplication) of all quantities
        Total Product Qty = PRODUCT(Sales[Quantity])

DAX ProductX:
            Returns the product of an expression evaluated for each row in a table.
Syntax:
                      PRODUCTX(<table, expression>)
EX: Multiply profit of each row and return final value.
          ProductX Profit = PRODUCTX(Sales, Sales[Price] - Sales[Cost])


 
DAX Count:
This function only accepts a column as an argument. The following types of values are counted in rows using the COUNT function:
•	Numbers, Dates, strings
•	It does not count empty/blank values.
Syntax:
           COUNT(<column>)
EX: 
Count= COUNT(Sales[PRODUCTID])

DAX CountX: 
Counts total rows of a set of expressions evaluated over a table.
Syntax:
            COUNTX(<table, expression>)
EX: Count rows where profit is calculated.
        Count Profit Rows = COUNT	X(Sales, Sales[Price] - Sales[Cost])

DAX CountBlank: 
 It counts blank rows present in the column
Syntax:
            COUNTBLANK(<column>)

EX:  Count how many blank values are in Price column.
         Blank Count = COUNTBLANK(Sales[Price])

DAX CountRows:
            Returns total number of rows in the table
Syntax:  
                  COUNTROWS([<table>])
EX: Find total number of rows in the table.
        Total Rows = COUNTROWS(Sales)


DAX DistinctCount: 
           Determines how many distinct values there are in a column.
Syntax:
             DISTINCTCOUNT(<column>)
 EX: Find number of unique products.
         Distinct Products = DISTINCTCOUNT(Sales[Product])



Divide: 
           It will divide numerator by denominator
Syntax:     
          DIVIDE(numerator, Denominator)
        EX: Find profit ratio (Total Profit / Total Cost).
                Profit Ratio = DIVIDE(
                      SUMX(Sales, (Sales[Price] - Sales[Cost]) * Sales[Quantity]),
                      SUMX(Sales, Sales[Cost] * Sales[Quantity]))

RELATED:  To access column from one table to another 
•	Both tables should be related by the means of relationship

 


Conditional And Logical functions:

IF 
       If condition is true do this, else do that.

Syntax: 
          IF (condition, true_result, false_result) 
EX:  
         If customer is earning less than 40000 then no card if more than 40000 give cards  
         Membership =IF(CustomerData[AnnualIncome] < 40000, "No Card", "Card")

Nested IF:
               When we need to check condition more than one then we go for nested if 
EX:  
         If customer is earning less than 40000 then low if less than 60000 medium if less than 80000 Premium  
         Customer Level =
                                      IF(CustomerData[AnnualIncome] < 40000, "Low",
                                      IF(CustomerData[AnnualIncome] < 60000, "Medium",
                                      IF(CustomerData[AnnualIncome] < 80000, "High”, “Premium")))

For multiple conditions:
SWITCH: 
            To avoid nested if we go for switch 
Syntax: 
              SWITCH(<expression>, <value>, <result>, [<value>, <result>]…[, <else>])
Ex:
       City Code =   SWITCH(
                                              CustomerData[City],
                                             "Chennai", "CH",
                                             "Bangalore", "BLR",
                                             "Mumbai", "MUM",
                                             "Hyderabad", "HYD",
                                             "Other")

COMMON MISTAKE:
                           
                  SWITCH (CustomerData [AnnualIncome], >50000, "High", >30000, "Medium")
•	This will throw error Because SWITCH expects exact match, not conditions
TRUE:
•	Used for conditions (> , < , etc.)
Works like multiple IF but cleaner


         Syntax: 
       SWITCH(TRUE(), condition1, result1, condition2, result2, else)

EX:
      Spending Category =
                                          SWITCH(
                                                          TRUE(),
                                                                      CustomerData[SpendingScore] > 80, "High",
                                                                      CustomerData[SpendingScore] > 60, "Medium",
                                                                      CustomerData[SpendingScore] < 40, "Low",
                                                                     "Average")


Logical Functions:

AND
        All conditions must be TRUE
Syntax: 
           AND(<CON1>, <CON2>) 

EX: Male and Income > 80000 → High value customer or else low valued customer
        Target Customer =IF (AND (
                                        CustomerData [Gender] = "Male", CustomerData [AnnualIncome] > 80000),
                                      "High", "Low")
Note: AND accepts only 2 arguments. Hence, we go for and operator (&&)
                         Target Customer = IF (
                                                              CustomerData[Gender] = "Male" &&
                                                              CustomerData [AnnualIncome] > 80000 &&
                                                               CustomerData[SpendingScore] > 70,
                                                               "Yes",  "No")

OR:
It will accept value if any one condition is TRUE
Syntax: 
       OR(<CON1>, <CON2>)

EX:  Male OR Income > 80000 → High value customer or else low valued customer
Target Customer =IF (OR (
                                    CustomerData [Gender] = "Male", CustomerData [AnnualIncome] > 80000),
                                    “High", "Low")
Note: OR accepts only 2 arguments. Hence, we go for or operator (||)

Target Customer =
IF (
    CustomerData [AnnualIncome] > 80000 ||
    CustomerData [SpendingScore] > 80,
    "Yes",
    "No")		

 

