 WEEKNUM
              It Returns week number to the given date 
Syntax 
     WEEKNUM(<date>, [<week start>])
     [<week start>] – It’ll tell when week start 
     1 – week starts from Sunday 
     2 – Week starts from Monday
    11 – Also from Monday, but we’ll use this for business calculations.
 


Ex: 
Using 1 (Sunday start)
Week1 = WEEKNUM(DATE(2023,1,1), 1)
 Week starts from Sunday
 Result: Week = 1

Using 2 (Monday start)
Week2 = WEEKNUM(DATE(2023,1,1), 2)
 Week starts from Monday
 Result: Week = 1

Case 3: Using 11 
Week3 = WEEKNUM(DATE(2023,1,1), 11)
 Result: Week = 52

•	1 and 2 → simple counting 
•	11 → follows strict week rule 
 Rule:
 Week belongs to year only if it has enough days
•	Jan 1 Sunday is alone 
•	Not a full week 
•	11 says → This belongs to last year (week 52)
•	Used in companies where week calculation follows strict business rules ISO-like calendar

	
•	WEEKDAY: It returns day as number from 1-7,where sun=1 and sat=7
EX: wn= WEEKDAY ('Calendar Lookup'[Date])



 

Filtering Funcions 

FILTER:
             It’ll select only rows that match a condition
        Syntax:    FILTER(<table>, <expression>)
•	<table>: The table you want to filter.
•	<expression>: A condition that rows in the table must meet to be included.
EX: Get employees with Salary > 40000
        High Salary Table =
                                       FILTER (EmployeeSalesData, EmployeeSalesData[Salary] > 40000)


CALCULATE:
            The CALCULATE function in DAX is used to perform a calculation with a condition
 SYNTAX: 
         CALCULATE(<expression>, <filter1>, <filter2>, ...)
Ex: Total Sales in IT department
IT Sales = CALCULATE (
                                            SUM (sheet1[Sales]),
                                            Sheet1 [Department] = "IT")
2. Sum of sales of IT employees in South region
   IT South Sales = CALCULATE (
                                              	         SUM(Sheet1[Sales]),
                                                       Sheet1 [Department] = "IT",
                                                       Sheet1 [Region] = "South")



3.ALL
 Removes all filters from a table or column.
SYNTAX:
     ALL (<table or column>)
Ex: Sum of sales from the table
         Total Sales All =
                                 CALCULATE (
                                 SUM (EmployeeSalesData [Sales]),
                                ALL(EmployeeSalesData))
 
Time intelligence
TOTALMTD (): (Total Month-To-Date)
                Calculates the total (sum) of an expression from the start of the current month to the selected date. If the selected date is 15 march it’ll calculate from 1 march to 15 march.
Syntax:
    TOTALMTD(<expression>, <dates>,[ <filter>])
Example:
   MTD Sales =
                        TOTALMTD(
                                               SUM(SalesDateData[Sales]),
                                               SalesDateData [Date])
•	Now it’ll calculate according to the last date.
•	Last date is August so it’ll calculate complete August month.

TOTALQTD () (Total Quarter-To-Date)
                    Computes the total (sum) of an expression from the start of the current quarter up to the selected date.
Syntax:
    TOTALQTD(<expression>, <dates>[, <filter>])

Ex:
      QTD Sales =
                           TOTALQTD(
                                                 SUM(SalesDateData[Sales]),
                                                  SalesDateData[Date] )


TOTALYTD () (Total Year-To-Date)

 Computes the total (sum) of an expression from the start of the year up to the selected date.
Syntax:
    TOTALYTD(<expression>, <dates>[, <year_end_date>])

Ex:
    	       YTD Sales =
                                        TOTALYTD(
                                                              SUM(SalesDateData[Sales]),
                                                               SalesDateData[Date]) 

Note: The 'year_end_date' parameter allows setting a fiscal year-end (e.g., "06-30" for June 30th).


 FIRSTDATE & LASTDATE:
                      Returns the first or last date in the current context.
             Syntax:    FIRSTDATE(<dates>)
                             LASTDATE(<dates>)


